    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-05-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-05-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="1294"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1294">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.1216M/421.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-05-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>220. The Department’s telegram of May 2 re Colorado River. Minister of Fomento
                    states he is in practical agreement with the Department’s counter-draft of the
                    amended convention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—On May 8, 1913, the Ambassador included in a
                            telegram<note n="1" xml:id="d1294fn1">This telegram is printed under
                            Political Affairs.</note> covering various subjects brought up in an
                        interview with General Huerta the information that Huerta had refused to
                        consider the Colorado River question until formal recognition of his
                        administration by the United States. No further action appears to have been
                        taken during 1913.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
